Measures -- t10 A Child-Centered Approach to Investigating Refugee Children’s Concerns -- t11 Qualitative and Quantitative Research among Hmong Refugees: An Analysis -- tConclusions and Implications for Future Research -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years, scholars in the fields of refugee studies and forced migration have extended their areas of interest and research into the phenomenon of displacement, human response to it, and ways to intervene to assist those affected, increasingly focusing on the emotional and social impact of displacement on refugees and their adjustment to the traumatic experiences. In the process, the positive concept of "psychosocial wellness" was developed as discussed in this volume. In it noted scholars address the strengths and limitations of their investigations, citing examples from their work with refugees from Afghanistan, Cambodia, Vietnam, Palestine, Cuba, Nicaragua, Haiti, Eastern Europe, Bosnia, and Chile. The authors discuss how they define "psychosocial wellness," as well as the issues of sample selection, measurement, reliability and validity, refugee narratives and "voices," and the ability to generalize findings and apply these to other populations. The key question that has guided many of these investigations and underlies the premise of this book is "what happens to an ordinary person who has experienced an extraordinary event?" This volume also highlights the fact that those involved in such research must also deal with their own emotional responses as they hear victims tell of killing, torture, humiliation, and dispossesion. The volume will therefore appeal to practitioners of psychology, psychiatry, social work, nursing, and anthropology. However, its breadth and the evaluation of the strengths and disadvantages of both qualitative and quantitative methods also make it an excellent text for students.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aMental health. 0aRefugeesxMental healthvCross-cultural studies. 0aRefugeesxMental healthxResearch. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aAger, Alastair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAhearn, Frederick L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeiser, Morton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBertrand, Didier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEastmond, Marita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrell-Bond, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHyman, Ilene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJr., Frederick L. Ahearn, Frederick L. Ahearn,, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLoughry, Maryanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacMullin, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoh, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOmidian, Patricia A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPotocky-Tripodi, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPunamäki, Raija-Leena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVu, Nhi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWestermeyer, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aXuan Nghia, Nguyen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178238804340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782388043423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782